            h4.
              About the Cambridge Cluster Map
          #page-about-content.modal-body
            img.centre(src='/img/AstraZeneca-scientist-for-About-modal.jpg' alt='AZ' style='display: block; margin: 0 auto; padding: 15px; max-width:100%;')

            span.image-credit
              p.
                Image: AstraZeneca

            p.abstract
                |The Cambridge Cluster Map is a big data resource highlighting the data on the cluster of businesses located within 20 miles of Cambridge, UK. It is a free-to-access online resource created by Cambridge Ahead and shows the vibrancy of the Cambridge technology and life science cluster. The underlying research has been provided by the Centre for Business Research of the University of Cambridge and business data has been sourced from the FAME database produced by Bureau Van Dijk. Platform and mapping analytics have been created by Trampoline Systems. We would like to thank our #[a(href="#", onClick="$('#page-about').modal('hide').one('hidden.bs.modal', function (e) { $('#page-supporters').modal()})") supporters].

                //- sponsor, #[a(href="#", target="_blank") xxxxx Company] and
            p
              //- |The Cluster Map is an improvement on a previous version from the Cambridge 2 You initiative and&nbsp;

              //- a(href="http://www.cambridgeahead.co.uk", target="_blank") Cambridge Ahead
              |Cambridge Ahead has created this Cluster Map because we have now been able to draw together accurate financial data covering the full range of Cambridge companies, both those based in Cambridge, and those trading in it. Find out #[a(href="http://www.cambridgeahead.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/About-Companies-Data-on-the-CCM.pdf", target="_blank") how we define them and the company data provided]. The map is also different from previous versions because the data and the map presentation of it is not just for the Tech sector, but for all the other economic sectors too.

            p
              |We cannot yet claim that the data covers the entire economy of Cambridge, because the company employment data is for the Cambridge companies&rsquo; global employment and we do not have data for sole traders, some elements of the public sector, and for employees of national and international companies with trading and research offices in Cambridge. Nevertheless, the growth trends over several years are strong indicators of the whole sub-regional economy&rsquo;s growth and we expect to add further data later that may enable this claim to be made. The data will be updated at least annually.

            p.
              The data means that we can show the growth and economic health of the sub-region over time much better than before. We now have real and detailed evidence that Cambridge companies have grown very rapidly in the past 4 years. Importantly, this growth does not include data on &lsquo;incomers&rsquo; to the city, such as AstraZeneca.

            p.
              The source, #[a(href='http://www.cambridgeahead.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/CBR-Database-Methodology-Feb-2016.pdf', target="_blank") methodology] and granular nature of the data means that the map will be of interest to a wide audience, from individual companies in Cambridge, to economics researchers, through to international organisations which might be doing a global search for new locations or acquisitions. There are 5 years of data, for which we are showing 4 years of growth.

            p.
              The map enables the data to be shown in sectoral, geographic, chart and other formats. The data for individual companies includes postcode, business sector, turnover, employment level, and directors.

            h5.
              Researchers

            p.
              Academic, economic, business and other researchers who wish to delve deeper into the data can do so by gaining accreditation from The Centre for Business Research (CBR). You will be able to access and download the data for further interrogation. In order to gain accreditation, please contact Dr Andy Cosh by completing this #[a(href='http://www.cambridgeahead.co.uk/camclustermap/contact', target="_blank") form].


